column3:
means that the VS Code task variables like %file%, %fileDirname%, etc., are not being replaced with your actual file paths. This is because in VS Code tasks, you should use ${file}, ${fileDirname}, etc. (with curly braces and a dollar sign), not the Windows batch-style %file%.
Your current tasks.json uses a cmd command with %file%, which does not work with VS Code's variable substitution.
column5:
%파일 %, %filedirname %등과 같은 VS 코드 작업 변수는 실제 파일 경로로 대체되지 않음을 의미합니다. 이는 대 코드 작업에서 Windows 배치 스타일 %파일 %가 아닌 $ {file}, $ {filedirname} 등 (곱슬 버팀대 및 달러 표시 포함)을 사용해야하기 때문입니다.
현재 tasks.json은 %파일 %가있는 CMD 명령을 사용하며, 이는 Code의 변수 대체와 함께 작동하지 않습니다.

column3: n Python, the built-in int type does not have a representation for infinity. Only floating-point numbers (float) can represent infinity, using float('inf').

column3: If you need an "infinite" integer for comparison purposes, you should use float('inf') or a very large integer value (like 10**18) depending on your use case. For most algorithms, float('inf') is the standard way to represent infinity in Python.

column3: The font-family property should hold several font names as a "fallback" system, to ensure maximum compatibility between browsers/operating systems. Start with the font you want, and end with a generic family (to let the browser pick a similar font in the generic family, if no other fonts are available). The font names should be separated with a comma. Read more about fallback fonts in the next chapter.
